{% block content %}
<header>
  <span class="icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-sun"></i></span>
  <h1>Joseph Smith's First Vision</h1>
  <p>The foundational event of the Restoration — a fourteen-year-old boy's prayer in a grove of trees, and what he claimed to see there in the spring of 1820.</p>
</header>

<main>

  <div class="intro-banner">
    <strong>The cornerstone of LDS claims.</strong> More than any other event, the First Vision stands at the center of what distinguishes Latter-day Saint Christianity from all other traditions. If it happened as Joseph Smith described, it changes everything. If it did not, the church falls with it. LDS leaders have said so themselves — and that is precisely why it matters for any serious comparison of LDS and mainstream Christian belief.
  </div>

  <!-- Background -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-book-open"></i> &nbsp;Background &amp; Context</div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p><strong>Western New York, 1820.</strong> The region where young Joseph Smith lived — later called the "Burned-over District" — was swept repeatedly by religious revivals. Methodists, Presbyterians, and Baptists competed vigorously for converts, and the intensity of the competing claims left the fourteen-year-old confused about which church to join.</p>
    <p><strong>The question.</strong> Joseph later wrote that he was especially troubled by James 1:5 — "If any of you lack wisdom, let him ask of God." Taking this at face value, he resolved to go into the woods near his family's farm in Manchester, New York, and ask God directly which church was true.</p>
    <p><strong>What followed.</strong> Joseph reported that he knelt in prayer in a clearing — since called the Sacred Grove — and after an initial experience of darkness, he saw a pillar of light descend, in which two personages appeared. He identified them as God the Father and Jesus Christ, both of whom, he said, spoke to him.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- The Vision in Joseph's own words -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-quote-left"></i> &nbsp;In Joseph's Own Words</div>
  <div class="quote-block">
    "I saw two Personages, whose brightness and glory defy all description, standing above me in the air. One of them spake unto me, calling me by name and said, pointing to the other — <em>This is My Beloved Son. Hear Him!</em>"
    <cite>— Joseph Smith–History 1:17, Pearl of Great Price (the 1838 account, canonized in LDS scripture)</cite>
  </div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p>According to Joseph's account, he then asked which church he should join. He was told to join none of them — that the churches then existing had all gone astray from the original gospel of Christ, and that a restoration of true Christianity would come through him. He was also told that his sins were forgiven.</p>
    <p>This answer — that <em>no existing church</em> held the complete truth — is the theological foundation for the LDS claim of a "Great Apostasy" followed by a divine Restoration. It is what makes the LDS church not simply a Protestant reformation, but a claim to be something categorically different.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Multiple accounts -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-scroll"></i> &nbsp;Multiple Historical Accounts</div>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1.2rem; line-height:1.7;">Joseph Smith told the story of his first vision several times across his life. These accounts differ in some details — a fact acknowledged by the LDS Church — and how one weighs those differences is a significant point of debate.</p>
  <div class="account-grid">
    <div class="account-card">
      <span class="ac-year">~1832</span>
      <h3>Earliest Written Account</h3>
      <p>Written in Joseph's own hand, this account focuses on forgiveness of sins and a vision of the Lord (Christ). God the Father is not explicitly described as a separate personage. Rediscovered in 1965.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="account-card">
      <span class="ac-year">1835</span>
      <h3>Account to Robert Matthias</h3>
      <p>Recorded in Joseph's journal. Mentions many angels, then two personages. Emphasizes the spiritual nature of the experience and includes the forgiveness of sins.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="account-card">
      <span class="ac-year">1838</span>
      <h3>Canonized Account</h3>
      <p>The most detailed and widely known version. Written for an official church history, this is the account published as Joseph Smith–History in the Pearl of Great Price and taught as the standard narrative.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="account-card">
      <span class="ac-year">1842</span>
      <h3>Wentworth Letter</h3>
      <p>A shorter public account written for a newspaper editor. States that God and Christ appeared but gives fewer details. More concise and apologetic in tone.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p><strong>How LDS scholars explain the differences.</strong> Church historians note that the accounts are consistent on the core claims — a vision occurred, divine beings appeared, Joseph was told not to join existing churches — while varying in emphasis and detail in ways typical of any person telling a story multiple times in different contexts.</p>
    <p><strong>How critics read the differences.</strong> Skeptics argue that the differences (especially regarding whether one or two beings appeared, and whether angels were present) suggest the story developed and grew over time, raising questions about historical reliability. The absence of any contemporary corroboration from 1820 is also frequently cited.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Theological significance -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-star"></i> &nbsp;Why It Matters Theologically</div>
  <div class="significance-list">
    <div class="sig-item">
      <div class="sig-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-people-group"></i></div>
      <div class="sig-body">
        <h4>God Has a Body</h4>
        <p>If the Father and Son appeared as two distinct, embodied personages, it overturns the traditional Christian doctrine that God is an incorporeal spirit. LDS theology holds that God the Father has a "body of flesh and bones as tangible as man's" (D&amp;C 130:22).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sig-item">
      <div class="sig-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-triangle-exclamation"></i></div>
      <div class="sig-body">
        <h4>The Great Apostasy</h4>
        <p>Being told that all existing churches had "gone astray" is the foundational claim that mainstream Christianity lost essential truth after the apostolic age — and that no existing church, however sincere, has authority to act in God's name.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sig-item">
      <div class="sig-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-key"></i></div>
      <div class="sig-body">
        <h4>Prophetic Authority</h4>
        <p>The vision establishes Joseph Smith as a prophet called directly by God — not ordained through existing ecclesiastical channels. Everything else in the LDS restoration (the Book of Mormon, priesthood keys, temples) flows from this foundational claim.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sig-item">
      <div class="sig-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-person-praying"></i></div>
      <div class="sig-body">
        <h4>God Answers Personal Prayer</h4>
        <p>For believing Latter-day Saints, the First Vision confirms that God is not distant or silent — He literally answered a teenager's sincere prayer. This shapes LDS spirituality's expectation of personal, experiential connection with God.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- LDS vs mainstream Christian perspective -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-scale-balanced"></i> &nbsp;Two Very Different Starting Points</div>
  <div class="compare-grid">
    <div class="compare-box">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-church"></i> Mainstream Christian View</h3>
      <p>No other tradition recognizes the First Vision as a genuine theophany. Most Christian theologians hold that the biblical canon is closed and that new prophetic revelation of this magnitude would require extraordinary, independently verifiable evidence. The event also directly contradicts classical Christian theology of God as immaterial and one undivided being.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-box">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-book-bible"></i> LDS View</h3>
      <p>Latter-day Saints regard the First Vision as the single most important event since the Resurrection. It is the lens through which all other LDS claims are understood. Members are encouraged to pray for a personal spiritual confirmation that it happened — and the testimony that it did is the foundation of LDS faith.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p><strong>The honest dividing line.</strong> This is not a debate that can be settled by historical evidence alone. Whether one believes the First Vision occurred depends ultimately on prior commitments about the possibility of modern prophetic revelation, the nature of spiritual experience, and whether one finds Joseph Smith's character and consistency trustworthy. Latter-day Saints and mainstream Christians are not simply disagreeing about one event — they are operating from fundamentally different epistemologies about how God speaks to humanity.</p>
  </div>

</main>

